50|$|Details {{released}} {{three months}} after the incident revealed the MiG-23s never turned on their onboard radars which were needed to guide their 12-mile-range AA-7 missiles. The turns by the Libyan pilots prior to the first missile launch by the F-14s were considered too slight to be deemed hostile according to <b>the</b> U.S. <b>House</b> <b>Armed</b> <b>Services</b> Committee Chairman Les Aspin. Despite these findings, Aspin said the self defense claim by the U.S. was still justified due to the MiG-23s continuously accelerating as they closed the distance with the F-14s, and because Libya had a history of firing first.|$|R
